# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: louisville-grays
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:louisville-grays/1876-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1876 throughout the world.
[src:louisville-grays/1876-in-baseball] After a tumultuous five-year existence, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) folded following the 1875 season.
[src:louisville-grays/1876-in-baseball] One of the new rules put into place by the new league was that all teams had to be located in cities that had a population of 75,000 or more.
[src:louisville-grays/1876-in-baseball] The initial NL season began with eight teams, and they were asked to play seventy games between April 22 and October 21.
[src:louisville-grays/1876-in-baseball] The NL is often considered to be the first "major league", although it has been argued that the NA can make that claim.
[src:louisville-grays/1876-louisville-grays-season] The **Louisville Grays** were formed prior to the 1876 Major League Baseball season and joined the just formed National League as a charter member.
[src:louisville-grays/1876-louisville-grays-season] They finished in fifth place in their debut season under manager Jack Chapman.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1877 throughout the world.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-season] The **1877 Louisville Grays** were the victim of Major League Baseball's first gambling scandal.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-season] Pitcher Jim Devlin, outfielder George Hall, utility player Al Nichols and shortstop Bill Craver were accused of throwing games at the end of the season.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-season] All four were banned from baseball for life.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-season] The team was unable to continue and folded after the season.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-season] After a spectacular start that included a 27–13 record to begin the season, the Grays mysteriously lost seven games in a row.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-season] Players bobbled the ball, seemed to slow between bases, and swung suspiciously wide.
[src:louisville-grays/1877-louisville-grays-season] The result was that the Grays lost the pennant.
[src:louisville-grays/19th-century-national-league-teams] The following is a list of United States **Major League Baseball teams that played in the National League during the 19th century**.
[src:louisville-grays/19th-century-national-league-teams] None of these teams, other than Athletic and Mutual, had actual names during this period; sportswriters however often applied creative monickers which are still, mistakenly, used today as "team names" following a convention established in 1951.
[src:louisville-grays/19th-century-national-league-teams] This lineup of teams remained the same from 1892 to the end of the 1899 season.
[src:louisville-grays/19th-century-national-league-teams] After the 1899 season Baltimore, Cleveland, Louisville and Washington were dropped from the National League.
[src:louisville-grays/19th-century-national-league-teams] This lineup remained the same until Boston relocated to Milwaukee in 1953.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] Nichols got his start at third base for the 1875 Brooklyn Atlantics of the National Association.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] He batted only .153 in 32 games played that season.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] The following year, after the collapse of the Association, he played for the New York Mutuals of the new National League and didn't fare much better, hitting .179 in 57 games.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] It was for the Louisville Grays in 1877 that he would gain infamy.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] It was determined that he was involved in throwing games for money along with teammates George Hall, Jim Devlin, and Bill Craver.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] As a personal friend of Hall, he was brought in to play third base at Hall's insistence to replace Bill Hauge when he had to take time off due to injury.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] At this point, Louisville was in first place, but soon after Nichols' arrival, the team began to lose games at an alarming rate.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] Chase started to become suspicious when Nichols was still playing even though he continued to make key errors when Hauge was well enough to return to his starting position.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] His suspicion was confirmed when he received a couple telegrams instructing him to watch his players.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] Chase confronted the players, and Hall and Devlin confessed.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] The matter was referred to National League president William Hulbert, and Nichols was formally banned from Major League Baseball on December 4, 1877.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] Nichols came to the United States from England in 1861.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] After his banishment from baseball, he spent most of his life in the Brooklyn, New York area, got married and raised a family.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] He worked at various jobs, including as a shipping clerk and inspector, and was very remorseful about his role in the scandal, making many unsuccessful attempts to earn reinstatement.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] He died in Richmond Hill, New York, at the age of 84.
[src:louisville-grays/al-nichols] He was cremated and interred at Green-Wood Cemetery in Brooklyn.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] The **Louisville Grays** were a 19th-century United States baseball team and charter member of the National League, based in Louisville, Kentucky.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] They played two seasons, 1876 and 1877, and compiled a record of 65–61.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] Their home games were at the Louisville Baseball Park.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] The Grays were owned by businessman Walter Newman Haldeman, owner and publisher of the *Louisville Courier-Journal* newspaper.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] The Grays were undone by Major League Baseball's first gambling scandal.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] The team was in first place in August 1877, then suddenly lost seven games and tied one against the Boston Red Stockings and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] Boston ended up winning the pennant, seven games ahead of the second-place Grays.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] A *Courier-Journal* story questioning the team's conduct was written by John Haldeman, the owner's son.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] Team president Charles Chase received two anonymous telegrams.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] One noted that gamblers were favoring the less talented Hartford team in an upcoming series.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] The second telegram predicted Louisville would throw the next game versus Hartford on August 21.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] The Grays committed a number of suspicious errors and lost that game 7–0.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] League president William Hulbert investigated and ordered players to authorize Western Union to release all telegrams sent or received during the 1877 season.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] All players complied except shortstop Bill Craver, the team's captain.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] The telegrams indicated that pitcher Jim Devlin, left fielder George Hall, and utility player Al Nichols intentionally lost games in exchange for money.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] No direct evidence was found implicating Craver.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] All four were banned from baseball for life, Craver for refusing to comply with the investigation.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] Devlin pitched every inning for the 1877 Grays, leading the league in games and innings pitched.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] Hall played every inning in left field; he was a good batter, and was the 1876 home run leader with five.
[src:louisville-grays/louisville-grays] Louis Brown Stockings had signed Devlin and Hall for 1878 and went out of business with the Grays after the investigation.
